00:05:52.690 --> 00:05:57.200
in Spain between 1952
and January 1953.

00:05:57.200 --> 00:06:00.340
The material resource of his
journey, which are preserved

00:06:00.340 --> 00:06:04.780
at the American Folk Life Center,
include music on magnetic tape,

00:06:04.780 --> 00:06:09.390
but also photographs, [inaudible],
invoices, annotated maps, letters,

00:06:09.390 --> 00:06:14.610
diaries, and even the manuscript
of part of a book for publication.

00:06:14.610 --> 00:06:18.700
Why did Lomax undertake
field working in Spain?

00:06:18.700 --> 00:06:20.350
Columbia Records had
commission [inaudible]

00:06:20.350 --> 00:06:24.160
to bring together a series
of folk music albums,

00:06:24.160 --> 00:06:28.080
each of which would be
devoted to a country or region.

00:06:28.080 --> 00:06:32.350
One of the albums would
be dedicated to Spain.

00:06:32.350 --> 00:06:35.760
Lomax wrote [inaudible]
musician and writer,

00:06:35.760 --> 00:06:39.780
director of the British
Council in Spain asking guidance

00:06:39.780 --> 00:06:42.400
to help him find a
Spanish folklorist

00:06:42.400 --> 00:06:45.030
with experience in field recording.

00:06:45.030 --> 00:06:48.770
On this light we can see
[inaudible] indicating

00:06:48.770 --> 00:06:51.040
that Spanish ethnic
musicologists continue

00:06:51.040 --> 00:06:52.720
to write the music down by hand.

00:06:52.720 --> 00:06:57.280
Given the possibility of
finding a collaborator

00:06:57.280 --> 00:07:01.300
with the required equipment and
experience, Lomax, who was living

00:07:01.300 --> 00:07:03.780
in Paris at that moment, decided

00:07:03.780 --> 00:07:06.630
to attend the attend the
Folklore [inaudible] Festival

00:07:06.630 --> 00:07:09.870
to be celebrated in
[inaudible] in June 1952

00:07:09.870 --> 00:07:14.250
as it would be a good
opportunity for networking.

00:07:14.250 --> 00:07:16.570
The coordinator of the
festival was [inaudible],

00:07:16.570 --> 00:07:20.690
a [inaudible] musicologist who
had been appointed director

00:07:20.690 --> 00:07:22.070
of the folklore division

00:07:22.070 --> 00:07:25.220
of the former Spanish
Institute of Musicology.

00:07:25.220 --> 00:07:27.570
According to Lomax, when Schneider
[assumed spelling] learned

00:07:27.570 --> 00:07:31.470
about his project he stated that
he would personally see to it

00:07:31.470 --> 00:07:35.320
that no Spanish musicologist
would help him.

00:07:35.320 --> 00:07:39.140
It was this encounter that
made Lomax promise himself

00:07:39.140 --> 00:07:41.270
that he would record in Spain.

00:07:41.270 --> 00:07:44.570
The main source of funding
was the BBC in London,

00:07:44.570 --> 00:07:47.480
which was planning a series
of broadcasts in Spain.

00:07:47.480 --> 00:07:52.270
Lomax offered to provide them with
recordings if they finance his trip

00:07:52.270 --> 00:07:57.290
and that of his British
assistant, [inaudible].

00:07:57.290 --> 00:08:00.570
The lack of cooperation from
the Spanish musicologist

00:08:00.570 --> 00:08:06.300
to whom Lomax referred leaves us to
wonder how he succeeded [inaudible]

00:08:06.300 --> 00:08:08.090
that allowed him to
complete his project.

00:08:08.090 --> 00:08:13.800 position:56%
It is also worth considering how his
approach to fieldwork defers to that

00:08:13.800 --> 00:08:16.300
of [inaudible] working in
Spain at the same time.

00:08:16.300 --> 00:08:21.230
The aim of my visit was
to answer these questions

00:08:21.230 --> 00:08:25.530
by analyzing the documents from
Lomax's Spain trip [inaudible]

00:08:25.530 --> 00:08:29.090
from oral history and
technological tools.

00:08:29.090 --> 00:08:31.330
These materials offer
a unique opportunity

00:08:31.330 --> 00:08:35.710
to approach the political situation
and the Francoist dictatorship,

00:08:35.710 --> 00:08:39.720
the poverty of the country, and the
moral constrictions faced by women

00:08:39.720 --> 00:08:41.580
through the eyes of
Lomax and [inaudible].

00:08:41.580 --> 00:08:46.580
Digital tools has been used in
order to establish connections

00:08:46.580 --> 00:08:49.870
between the songs recorded by
Lomax and other collections

00:08:49.870 --> 00:08:53.970
of Spanish traditional music
compiled around the same time,

00:08:53.970 --> 00:08:57.180
such as [inaudible] at the
Spanish National Research Council

00:08:57.180 --> 00:08:58.740
in Barcelona.

00:08:58.740 --> 00:09:02.070
The Barcelona collection is
primarily made up of more

00:09:02.070 --> 00:09:06.300 position:56%
than 20,000 folksongs copied on
paper and collected throughout Spain

00:09:06.300 --> 00:09:10.670
between 1944 and 1960, most of them

00:09:10.670 --> 00:09:14.290
through the so-called folkloric
missions and competitions organized

00:09:14.290 --> 00:09:16.980
by the former Spanish
Institute of Musicology.

00:09:16.980 --> 00:09:22.400
Since 2011 I have been involved
in the project to digitize

00:09:22.400 --> 00:09:24.430
and catalogue the Barcelona
collection

00:09:24.430 --> 00:09:26.280
in an open access database.

00:09:26.280 --> 00:09:30.020
As the first stage of my research
at the Library of Congress,

00:09:30.020 --> 00:09:33.750
I have incorporated the details
provided by the Lomax collection

00:09:33.750 --> 00:09:36.610
into the same database,
cataloging information

00:09:36.610 --> 00:09:40.730
on all the places visited by
Lomax in Spain and all the songs

00:09:40.730 --> 00:09:44.810 position:56%
and people recorded there, including
his [inaudible] on the Association

00:09:44.810 --> 00:09:49.830
for Cultural Equity Online Archive.

00:09:49.830 --> 00:09:53.300
The material was catalogued
by listening to the songs

00:09:53.300 --> 00:09:56.910
and consulting Lomax's notes
on the [inaudible] boxes along

00:09:56.910 --> 00:09:59.060
with his diaries and notebooks.

00:09:59.060 --> 00:10:03.770
Some of the songs were broadcast
into series of programs by the BBC.

00:10:03.770 --> 00:10:07.050
The song commentaries were
cited in the database as well

00:10:07.050 --> 00:10:10.050
as the notes included in the
albums that were published

00:10:10.050 --> 00:10:11.830
by Lomax or edited later.

00:10:11.830 --> 00:10:17.010
I also analyze catalogue
and transcribe documents

00:10:17.010 --> 00:10:20.120
such as field notebooks,
annotated maps, letters,

00:10:20.120 --> 00:10:23.450
and diaries connecting
them to the music, people,

00:10:23.450 --> 00:10:26.520
and locations to which they
refer, and including links

00:10:26.520 --> 00:10:30.150
to the corresponding [inaudible]
on the Library of Congress website.

00:10:30.150 --> 00:10:34.970 position:56%
Lomax's writings offer contradictory
details regarding his itinerary

00:10:34.970 --> 00:10:38.710
