and institutional support.

00:17:42.190 --> 00:17:47.350
Lomax's network of contacts in
Spain included musicologists,

00:17:47.350 --> 00:17:50.460 position:56%
but [inaudible] procession of
people such as artists, journalists,

00:17:50.460 --> 00:17:55.230
anthropologists, and even people
who he have just met on his arrival

00:17:55.230 --> 00:18:00.090
in a town and acted
as spontaneous guides.

00:18:00.090 --> 00:18:03.800 position:56%
He had [inaudible] Lomax's
assistant, in this journey commented

00:18:03.800 --> 00:18:09.590
that she never really knew how he
got hold of all the people he did.

00:18:09.590 --> 00:18:12.540
Lomax's documents contain
constant references to [inaudible]

00:18:12.540 --> 00:18:16.130
and reflect the important
role that she played

00:18:16.130 --> 00:18:20.370 position:56%
in helping Spanish women open up for
the recordings and talk about topics

00:18:20.370 --> 00:18:22.920
that they would never have
discussed with [inaudible].

00:18:22.920 --> 00:18:27.160
A part of my research consisted
of analyzing how women,

00:18:27.160 --> 00:18:29.880
from their own spaces,
contributing to setting --

00:18:29.880 --> 00:18:34.410
contributed to setting
up this collection.

00:18:34.410 --> 00:18:37.220
[Inaudible] writing are scattered
among Lomax's papers so that

00:18:37.220 --> 00:18:42.010
at first they could be confused
with text written by Lomax himself.

00:18:42.010 --> 00:18:44.120
They begin with a description
of [inaudible] arrival

00:18:44.120 --> 00:18:49.400
in Barcelona Airport in August
1952, and an encounter with Lomax.

00:18:49.400 --> 00:18:53.160
They also contain comments on her
experiences through her journey,

00:18:53.160 --> 00:18:56.690
her role in the recording
process, and her feelings.

00:18:56.690 --> 00:19:00.580
These memoirs demonstrate her
connections with Spanish women.

00:19:00.580 --> 00:19:03.970
For instance, learning to dance
with young girls or trying

00:19:03.970 --> 00:19:06.400
on traditional women's costumes.

00:19:06.400 --> 00:19:09.200
She also explained her
experience when Lomax left her

00:19:09.200 --> 00:19:13.180
to record a group of young
girls on her own and even wrote

00:19:13.180 --> 00:19:16.290
that Spanish women were the
nicest people she had ever met.

00:19:16.290 --> 00:19:21.090
[Inaudible] was also
skilled at talking with men.

00:19:21.090 --> 00:19:24.200
For example, when Lomax reported
on his field work in the north

00:19:24.200 --> 00:19:28.980
of Spain he wrote that while
he recorded a young man told

00:19:28.980 --> 00:19:31.840
[inaudible] some of the things
[inaudible] wouldn't have told him

00:19:31.840 --> 00:19:35.230
about the sex life in the area.

00:19:35.230 --> 00:19:38.620
[Inaudible] memoirs are very rich
in comments on the particularities

00:19:38.620 --> 00:19:39.920
of Spanish family culture.

00:19:39.920 --> 00:19:43.650
To give an example,
26 year old widow

00:19:43.650 --> 00:19:45.960
from the [inaudible]
region explained to her

00:19:45.960 --> 00:19:49.360
that before marrying women used
to have a boyfriend for more

00:19:49.360 --> 00:19:54.070
than 10 years and that when
a husband died his wife had

00:19:54.070 --> 00:19:56.710
to wear black clothes forever.

00:19:56.710 --> 00:19:59.490
Spanish women talk
about their lives,

00:19:59.490 --> 00:20:02.970
but also sang songs
related to their customs.

00:20:04.510 --> 00:20:30.560
[ Music ]

00:20:30.560 --> 00:20:34.860
Lomax showed a special interest in
Spanish women's lives and explained

00:20:34.860 --> 00:20:39.060
that in his worldwide field work
he found feature of song and dance

00:20:39.060 --> 00:20:41.820
that are specific to women.

00:20:41.820 --> 00:20:45.260
When he recorded [inaudible] he
always asked the female singer

00:20:45.260 --> 00:20:48.020
to hold a child in her arms.

00:20:48.020 --> 00:20:49.630
Women played an important role

00:20:49.630 --> 00:20:54.570
in the oral transmission
of music in Spain.

00:20:54.570 --> 00:20:57.690
The clear [inaudible] of the
Barcelona collection were women

00:20:57.690 --> 00:21:00.140
and they have learned the
songs from their mothers

00:21:00.140 --> 00:21:02.510 position:56%
or grandmothers or from other girls.

00:21:02.510 --> 00:21:08.500
To conclude, the material results

00:21:08.500 --> 00:21:12.760
of Lomax's Spain trip can only
barely reflect the deep impact

00:21:12.760 --> 00:21:15.260
that his visit must have
had on the habitants

00:21:15.260 --> 00:21:17.840
of the small villages
where he recorded.

00:21:17.840 --> 00:21:20.780
His amazing legacy can
complement other collections

00:21:20.780 --> 00:21:25.010
of Spanish folk music compiled
on paper in the same period.

00:21:25.010 --> 00:21:27.680
Lomax's itinerary reflects
concordances

00:21:27.680 --> 00:21:28.980
with the fieldwork carried

00:21:28.980 --> 00:21:32.190
out by Spanish researchers
whose [inaudible] from part

00:21:32.190 --> 00:21:33.990
of the Barcelona collection.

00:21:33.990 --> 00:21:38.530
However, these concordances
have a very limited scope.

00:21:38.530 --> 00:21:41.560
This is probably due to
the [inaudible] of people

00:21:41.560 --> 00:21:45.800
who follow Lomax's contact
network to his limited relationship

00:21:45.800 --> 00:21:49.190
with Spanish musicologists and
to his concept of folklore.

00:21:49.190 --> 00:21:52.780
The approach to the
[inaudible] and singing of women

00:21:52.780 --> 00:21:55.570
through the otherness of
Lomax and [inaudible] suggest

00:21:55.570 --> 00:21:59.500
that oral tradition is a key
question that must be asked

00:21:59.500 --> 00:22:03.050
to challenge the loss of women's
voices in historical accounts

00:22:03.050 --> 00:22:06.370
and to place women on
the map of music history.

00:22:06.370 --> 00:22:13.850 position:56%
The accessibility of this collection
[inaudible] easily researchable

00:22:13.850 --> 00:22:16.740
and interactive platform
through the database

00:22:16.740 --> 00:22:21.640
and the map application will allow
researchers [inaudible] school

00:22:21.640 --> 00:22:26.900
teachers, folk music performance,
and the community in general to use

00:22:26.900 --> 00:22:30.960
and enjoy this magnificent
collection increasing a

00:22:30.960 --> 00:22:32.440
sociological impact.

00:22:32.440 --> 00:22:34.240
Thank you.

00:22:34.240 --> 00:22:50.130
[ Applause ]

00:22:50.130 --> 00:22:51.430
&gt;&gt; Chet Van Duzer: Hello.

00:22:51.430 --> 00:22:53.870
Thank you all for coming.

00:22:53.870 --> 00:22:57.300
Changing subjects a little bit,

00:22:57.300 --> 00:23:02.190
although Ascension did show an
annotated map, a map annotated

00:23:02.190 --> 00:23:07.080
by Lomax, so we have that
commonality working for us.

00:23:07.080 --> 00:23:09.070
I'll be talking to
you this afternoon

00:23:09.070 --> 00:23:13.550
about an extraordinary book,
a copy of Ptolemy's Geography,

00:23:13.550 --> 00:23:20.430 position:56%
the 1525 edition which is held by
Princeton in the university library.

00:23:20.430 --> 00:23:22.810
And it is very, very
heavily annotated,

00:23:22.810 --> 00:23:26.870
has many handwritten
annotations on it as you'll see.

00:23:26.870 --> 00:23:33.000
Ptolemy's Geography, when it was
rediscovered in Byzantium about --

00:23:33.000 --> 00:23:36.710
in about 1300, and then spread
across Europe in the 14th

00:23:36.710 --> 00:23:40.410
and 15th century in both a
manuscript and printed editions,

00:23:40.410 --> 00:23:43.770
it became the most
important geographical text

00:23:43.770 --> 00:23:45.820
of the European renaissance.

00:23:45.820 --> 00:23:49.600
And on the one hand, there was
a great enthusiasm for the work.

00:23:49.600 --> 00:23:52.590
It was reproduced in
many manuscripts

00:23:52.590 --> 00:23:55.190
and a great abundance
of printed editions.

00:23:55.190 --> 00:23:58.220
But on the other hand, there was
a dissatisfaction with the work,

00:23:58.220 --> 00:24:03.880
specifically as regards the fact
that it's a mathematical geography.

00:24:03.880 --> 00:24:05.990
It's not very descriptive at all.

00:24:05.990 --> 00:24:11.150 position:56%
The work consists of text that gives
instructions on how to make maps

00:24:11.150 --> 00:24:15.980 position:56%
and a database of 8000 locations
with their latitudes and longitudes.

00:24:15.980 --> 00:24:18.810
So very little in the
way of description.

00:24:18.810 --> 00:24:22.390
And so the work came to be
supplemented in various ways.

00:24:22.390 --> 00:24:26.300
And one of those ways was
annotation, as we see here.

00:24:26.300 --> 00:24:29.680
So here's the Ptolemaic
map of Spain in the book,

00:24:29.680 --> 00:24:33.040
and in case you can't see it
immediately, all of the text

00:24:33.040 --> 00:24:36.260
that I've highlighted
is handwritten,

00:24:36.260 --> 00:24:38.790
supplementary, descriptive
information.

00:24:38.790 --> 00:24:42.130
So it's really an extraordinary
book.

00:24:42.130 --> 00:24:45.650
Looking at a few other
maps from this book.

00:24:45.650 --> 00:24:47.300
Here's the Ptolemaic world map.

00:24:47.300 --> 00:24:53.210
And as you can see, it's surrounded
by handwritten supplementary texts.

00:24:53.210 --> 00:24:57.200
The texts are not only on
the maps themselves but also

00:24:57.200 --> 00:24:59.170
on black pages following the maps.

00:24:59.170 --> 00:25:02.610
The annotator was that enthusiastic
and he had so much to say

00:25:02.610 --> 00:25:05.530
that he also wrote
on following pages.

00:25:05.530 --> 00:25:12.850
The text, as I said, was printed --
this edition was printed in 1525.

00:25:12.850 --> 00:25:15.680
The annotations were
composed in 1527.

00:25:15.680 --> 00:25:19.040
At one point the annotators
refers to a historical event

00:25:19.040 --> 00:25:24.940
as having taken place last summer,
and that event took place in 1526.

00:25:24.940 --> 00:25:28.260
I want to point out here, this is
something I'll return to later,

00:25:28.260 --> 00:25:31.440
that what Princeton has
is really half the book.

00:25:31.440 --> 00:25:35.200
So we can see a visible
difference in the paper

00:25:35.200 --> 00:25:37.240
in the two parts of the book here.

00:25:37.240 --> 00:25:41.530 position:56%
And what have is the end of the text
block on the left and the beginning

00:25:41.530 --> 00:25:43.410
of the maps on the right.

00:25:43.410 --> 00:25:47.810
So at some point in the book's
history a dealer had these

00:25:47.810 --> 00:25:49.650
annotated maps.

00:25:49.650 --> 00:25:52.500
He realized that in order
to get the full value

00:25:52.500 --> 00:25:54.940
out of selling the book
it had to be complete.

00:25:54.940 --> 00:25:57.100
So he took the text
from another copy

00:25:57.100 --> 00:25:59.460 position:56%
and bound it together with the maps.

00:25:59.460 --> 00:26:02.900
So we have in the Princeton
copy the annotated maps

00:26:02.900 --> 00:26:07.560
with unannotated text
from a different copy.

00:26:07.560 --> 00:26:10.980
So what does all this text say?

00:26:10.980 --> 00:26:13.860
Well, it's -- he's
adding very substantial

00:26:13.860 --> 00:26:16.000
and very detailed descriptive text

00:26:16.000 --> 00:26:20.610
to Ptolemy's basically mathematical
description of the world.

00:26:20.610 --> 00:26:23.850
So just to look at a few examples.

00:26:23.850 --> 00:26:29.630
On the third map of Africa,
looking at this text, add, he says,

00:26:29.630 --> 00:26:33.310 position:56%
and that's an instruction to the
student, these annotations were made

00:26:33.310 --> 00:26:36.370
for a student, which is one of
the most interesting aspects,

00:26:36.370 --> 00:26:40.980
add right in this book that
the map above is defective,

00:26:40.980 --> 00:26:44.850
for there where I put this
sign, the one I've circled,

00:26:44.850 --> 00:26:52.330
is the Aphroditopolites nome and a
landlocked metropolis between which

00:26:52.330 --> 00:26:54.620
and Crocodilopolis,
towards the Nile,

00:26:54.620 --> 00:26:57.000
there was a Lake Mirios
about which below.

00:26:57.000 --> 00:27:00.530
And then on the map
he places that sign

00:27:00.530 --> 00:27:03.710
to the location where
this text applies.

00:27:03.710 --> 00:27:10.280
Looking at another example, the
Ptolemaic fourth map of Asia,

00:27:10.280 --> 00:27:13.200
looking at the text
in the left margin.

00:27:13.200 --> 00:27:17.430
He says, not far from Tripoli there
is a field that Strabo calls Marca

00:27:17.430 --> 00:27:21.180
in which Posidonius says
a dead dragon was seen.

00:27:21.180 --> 00:27:25.190
It covered half an acre, and was
so thick that men mounted on horses

00:27:25.190 --> 00:27:27.550
on either side could
not see each other.

00:27:27.550 --> 00:27:30.870
Its mouth was large enough to
receive a man riding a horse,

00:27:30.870 --> 00:27:35.230
and each scale of its skin
was larger than a shield.

00:27:35.230 --> 00:27:38.620
So this really couldn't be any
more different from Ptolemy's text,

00:27:38.620 --> 00:27:42.360
this long list of 8000 places with
their latitudes and longitudes.

00:27:42.360 --> 00:27:47.370
He's giving a historical,
descriptive information,

00:27:47.370 --> 00:27:51.460
including about, if you would
say, the animals or monsters

00:27:51.460 --> 00:27:53.140
that were thought to live
in a particular region.

00:27:53.140 --> 00:27:57.910
Looking at the Ptolemaic
map of Spain.

00:27:57.910 --> 00:28:00.230
Again in the left margin, he says,

00:28:00.230 --> 00:28:03.620 position:56%
there is great confusion among
different authors regarding the name

00:28:03.620 --> 00:28:06.670
of the promontory in
Spain that faces west.

00:28:06.670 --> 00:28:08.810
And he goes on to discuss

00:28:08.810 --> 00:28:12.060 position:56%
in considerable detail the different
opinions regarding the name

00:28:12.060 --> 00:28:17.160 position:56%
of this promontory of Ptolemy, Mela,
Pliny, Solinus, Aelian, and Strabo.

00:28:17.160 --> 00:28:21.410
So he's very engaged with
classical literature,

00:28:21.410 --> 00:28:24.750
and we'll see more
evidence of that later.

00:28:24.750 --> 00:28:27.750
The map of the Atlantic
and the New World.

00:28:27.750 --> 00:28:29.700
Again, we can see very
heavy annotation.

00:28:29.700 --> 00:28:33.500
And these annotations are some of
the most interesting in the book.

00:28:33.500 --> 00:28:37.100
He talks -- he's talking about
the discovery of the New World

00:28:37.100 --> 00:28:42.230
and the discovery of the route
from Europe around Africa to Asia.

00:28:42.230 --> 00:28:45.590
And what he says is that
these are not new discoveries,

00:28:45.590 --> 00:28:51.240
that both of these things, the
New World and the route to Asia

00:28:51.240 --> 00:28:53.690
around Africa, had been
discovered in antiquity.

00:28:53.690 --> 00:28:58.230 position:56%
And so he makes little of the recent
Spanish and Portuguese discoveries.

00:28:58.230 --> 00:29:03.010
On the preceding page, that is
the page just before this map

00:29:03.010 --> 00:29:06.060
of the New World, he writes,
remark, as I often said,

00:29:06.060 --> 00:29:09.440
that neither this route to the
west, nor that of the Portuguese

00:29:09.440 --> 00:29:12.700
around the tip of Africa, is
new, but had already been done

00:29:12.700 --> 00:29:16.930
by other ancients, then abandoned,
and now finally in our times taken

00:29:16.930 --> 00:29:20.950 position:56%
up again, as is clear from
Aristotle, a most celebrated witness

00:29:20.950 --> 00:29:23.420
and a noble author for
increasing one's confidence.

00:29:23.420 --> 00:29:30.360
And on the map himself he
says, along these same lines,

00:29:30.360 --> 00:29:33.030
we will venture, based on
the excerpts from Aristotle

00:29:33.030 --> 00:29:36.110
that I transcribed below,
that the men and women found

00:29:36.110 --> 00:29:40.010
in this new land were Carthaginians
by origin, and that afterwards,

00:29:40.010 --> 00:29:43.190
left alone and deprived of
communication with other peoples,

00:29:43.190 --> 00:29:46.650
they became savages and gradually
lost their customs and rites

00:29:46.650 --> 00:29:51.130
and the use of clothing
through long desuetude.

00:29:51.130 --> 00:29:56.740
So this question is of where the
peoples of the New World came from?

00:29:56.740 --> 00:29:59.660
If all people were
descended from Adam and Eve

00:29:59.660 --> 00:30:02.030
and Columbus was the first
to reach the New World,

00:30:02.030 --> 00:30:04.160
where did the people
living there come from?

00:30:04.160 --> 00:30:07.060
And what he's saying is that
they were Carthaginians.

00:30:07.060 --> 00:30:11.610
That they're Carthaginians,
this [inaudible] work claimed

00:30:11.610 --> 00:30:15.240
that Carthaginian sailors
encountered a large land mass

00:30:15.240 --> 00:30:17.830
in the Atlantic, and
what he was concluding is

00:30:17.830 --> 00:30:22.490
that that was how the
New World was peopled.

00:30:22.490 --> 00:30:26.760
The annotator had a
strong character.

00:30:26.760 --> 00:30:31.830
He -- as we saw, he is very
content to disagree with Ptolemy.

00:30:31.830 --> 00:30:36.780
He also did not hesitate to
voice was rather strong opinions

00:30:36.780 --> 00:30:41.710
about the peoples who lived
in the maps in Ptolemy.

00:30:41.710 --> 00:30:45.470
So if we look at the modern map
of France, he has drawn a banner

00:30:45.470 --> 00:30:48.840
across the top which says, this
province produces a great number

00:30:48.840 --> 00:30:53.060
of chicken farmers,
innkeepers, cooks, flute-players,

00:30:53.060 --> 00:30:55.510
gamblers, drunkards, and fools.

00:30:55.510 --> 00:30:59.040
[ Laughter ]

00:30:59.040 --> 00:31:01.290
The modern map of Spain.

00:31:01.290 --> 00:31:04.810
He says here, the best thing for
one's financial affairs is not

00:31:04.810 --> 00:31:07.540
to take a loan from a
Catalan merchant [laughter].

00:31:08.780 --> 00:31:12.530
And there are similar statements
on a number of the maps.

00:31:12.530 --> 00:31:17.320 position:56%
They're all negative except for
one, which is -- I'll mention later,

00:31:17.320 --> 00:31:20.230
he -- across one of the
maps of Italy he says

00:31:20.230 --> 00:31:24.150
that heroic virtue is
innate to Italian blood.

00:31:24.150 --> 00:31:26.450
Guess where he was from [laughter]?

00:31:27.880 --> 00:31:30.160
So some of -- not all of
the maps are annotated.

00:31:30.160 --> 00:31:33.810
We saw that a number of them are
very, very heavily annotated.

00:31:33.810 --> 00:31:36.470
Some of them have no
annotations at all.

00:31:36.470 --> 00:31:38.800
And we can't be certain because --

00:31:38.800 --> 00:31:40.770
whether that was because
the annotator was not

00:31:40.770 --> 00:31:42.640
so interested in those regions.

00:31:42.640 --> 00:31:46.070
It's also possible that he
just didn't finish the program

00:31:46.070 --> 00:31:48.570
of annotation he had in mind.

00:31:48.570 --> 00:31:53.120
But the fact, I'm inclined to
think that we can read something

00:31:53.120 --> 00:31:54.830
into the fact that
they're not annotated,

00:31:54.830 --> 00:31:56.980
because if they had been priorities

00:31:56.980 --> 00:31:59.890
for him he would have
come to them sooner.

00:31:59.890 --> 00:32:01.800
So the Ptolemaic map of Taprobana.

00:32:01.800 --> 00:32:04.090
There was an abundance
of classical material

00:32:04.090 --> 00:32:06.250
that he could've added
to the map here.

00:32:06.250 --> 00:32:07.680
He did not.

00:32:07.680 --> 00:32:10.390
And I take this as evidence
that his real interest was

00:32:10.390 --> 00:32:11.970
in the Mediterranean Basin,

00:32:11.970 --> 00:32:15.230
which was where the classical
civilizations of Greece

00:32:15.230 --> 00:32:17.850
and Rome were most active.

00:32:17.850 --> 00:32:20.430
The modern map of the Holy
Land has no annotations.

00:32:20.430 --> 00:32:24.410
I think that's quite surprising
in 16th century Europe.

00:32:24.410 --> 00:32:27.950
So, again, his interest
was classical antiquity,

00:32:27.950 --> 00:32:30.610
not religious history.

00:32:30.610 --> 00:32:32.980
The modern map of Southern Africa.

00:32:32.980 --> 00:32:36.880 position:56%
Another -- from another annotator we
might have expected some text here

00:32:36.880 --> 00:32:39.710
about Portuguese voyages
around Africa.

00:32:39.710 --> 00:32:45.330 position:56%
As we saw, he thought little of
those voyages so it's not surprising

00:32:45.330 --> 00:32:47.280
that he makes no remark here.

00:32:47.280 --> 00:32:52.490
Looking at a few of the
sources of the annotations.

00:32:52.490 --> 00:32:56.840
One of his most -- the
book that he had to resort

00:32:56.840 --> 00:33:01.250
to most frequently was Caelius
Rhodiginus' Antiquarum Lectionum

00:33:01.250 --> 00:33:03.340
Libri IVI books.

00:33:03.340 --> 00:33:07.440
It's basically an encyclopedia.

00:33:07.440 --> 00:33:11.360
It's a very poorly organized
encyclopedia with quotations

00:33:11.360 --> 00:33:18.400
from classical authors on an
enormous variety of subjects.

00:33:18.400 --> 00:33:21.510
And when I go through the
annotations and I find

00:33:21.510 --> 00:33:22.970 position:56%
that he's citing a classical author,

00:33:22.970 --> 00:33:26.710
I have to check whether he's
citing the author directly

00:33:26.710 --> 00:33:31.550
or citing the classical author
by way of this book for example.

00:33:31.550 --> 00:33:37.390
A very similar book in terms of
its nature that is consisting

00:33:37.390 --> 00:33:41.910
of enormous masses of quotations
from classical authors is this book

00:33:41.910 --> 00:33:46.750
by Sabelico, another work
of encyclopedic nature.

00:33:46.750 --> 00:33:52.690
This is the title page of
the edition of Pomponius Mela

00:33:52.690 --> 00:33:56.920
with annotations by the
Swiss scholar Vadianus.

00:33:56.920 --> 00:33:58.890
This was another of
his favorite sources.

00:33:58.890 --> 00:34:02.510
And he makes use not
only of Pomponius Mela,

00:34:02.510 --> 00:34:07.910
the Roman geographer, but also
Vadianus' commentary on Mela.

00:34:07.910 --> 00:34:12.740
And Giovanni Pontano's Dialogi,
that's the source of some

00:34:12.740 --> 00:34:15.630
of his insulting comments about
the peoples of various regions.

00:34:15.630 --> 00:34:18.320
So he's a humanist scholar.

00:34:18.320 --> 00:34:23.210
He doesn't just take an
insult he heard on the street.

00:34:23.210 --> 00:34:29.010
He has a source, a classical -- a
literary source for his insults.

00:34:29.010 --> 00:34:35.210
The care spent on the
annotations, one of the nice things

00:34:35.210 --> 00:34:38.020
about this project is that
the annotations were written

00:34:38.020 --> 00:34:41.040
by a scribe, which is
somewhat surprising.

00:34:41.040 --> 00:34:45.430
It has the great benefit of making
most of the text pretty legible.

00:34:45.430 --> 00:34:49.000
And just to compare the hand

00:34:49.000 --> 00:34:51.490
in which these annotations
were written, that is the hand

00:34:51.490 --> 00:34:55.760
of a scribe, with those in another
annotated Ptolemy that's a little

00:34:55.760 --> 00:35:00.100
bit more typical, we see
here the difficult hand

00:35:00.100 --> 00:35:03.370
of a scholar's annotation in
a different copy of Ptolemy,

00:35:03.370 --> 00:35:05.890
much more difficult to read.

00:35:05.890 --> 00:35:11.050
So the mere fact that a scribe
was hired to write these text

00:35:11.050 --> 00:35:14.730
into this copy of the
book bespeaks a project

00:35:14.730 --> 00:35:19.330
with a lot of money to play with.

00:35:19.330 --> 00:35:21.010
Modern map of eastern India.

00:35:21.010 --> 00:35:25.040
Looking at the text on the
following page the annotator says,

00:35:25.040 --> 00:35:28.500
in addition to what was said on
the four other maps of India,

00:35:28.500 --> 00:35:31.990
I think it is here worth adding a
few words regarding the fertility

00:35:31.990 --> 00:35:33.290
of that land.

00:35:33.290 --> 00:35:36.210
My point here is that he's
referring to the text he wrote

00:35:36.210 --> 00:35:38.540
on the other four maps of India.

00:35:38.540 --> 00:35:41.910
It's a whole planned
program of annotations.

00:35:41.910 --> 00:35:47.690
It's not just casual remarks that
he made as they occurred to him.

00:35:47.690 --> 00:35:52.020
The Ptolemaic world map
that I showed earlier.

00:35:52.020 --> 00:35:56.220
Tremendous care was devoted
to the planning and layout

00:35:56.220 --> 00:35:58.150
of the annotations on this page.

00:35:58.150 --> 00:36:00.980
At the top and bottom we
have symmetrical quotations

00:36:00.980 --> 00:36:03.710
from Vitruvius about the
inhabitants of the northern

00:36:03.710 --> 00:36:06.170
and southern parts of the world.

00:36:06.170 --> 00:36:10.960
We have these triangular boxes
at the corners of the map.

00:36:10.960 --> 00:36:14.960
It's no accident that the text
fits in those triangles so neatly.

00:36:14.960 --> 00:36:20.490
He has a little title to
the annotations that run

00:36:20.490 --> 00:36:21.920
down the left and right margins.

00:36:21.920 --> 00:36:24.470
At the left we have
on the Hyperboreans.

00:36:24.470 --> 00:36:26.300
On the right on the Antipodes.

00:36:26.300 --> 00:36:30.160
And I want to point out that the
text is perfectly symmetrical.

00:36:30.160 --> 00:36:33.840
So it runs down the margins
and then into the lower margins

00:36:33.840 --> 00:36:35.900
and it ends at symmetrical points.

00:36:35.900 --> 00:36:38.840
And this, again, was -- it
didn't happen by accident.

00:36:38.840 --> 00:36:41.190
It was all very carefully planned.

00:36:41.190 --> 00:36:46.720
So we're talking about a project to
which very substantial resources,

00:36:46.720 --> 00:36:48.970
both of time and money,
were devoted.

00:36:48.970 --> 00:36:53.350
The purpose of the
annotations, as I mentioned,

00:36:53.350 --> 00:36:56.720
these annotations are unusual in
that they were made for a student.

00:36:56.720 --> 00:37:00.790
So what we have in this book is a
program of geographical education

00:37:00.790 --> 00:37:02.360
in the early 16th century.

00:37:02.360 --> 00:37:03.940
It's really quite extraordinary.

00:37:03.940 --> 00:37:05.570
And I want to look at
some of the evidence

00:37:05.570 --> 00:37:08.400
that the annotations
were made for a student.

00:37:08.400 --> 00:37:16.040
On the third map of Africa, in the
lower left, the annotator writes,

00:37:16.040 --> 00:37:19.740
where I added the Nasamones,
who were missing,

00:37:19.740 --> 00:37:23.260
so that you would know
the custom of this people.

00:37:23.260 --> 00:37:25.210
So he's addressing the student.

00:37:25.210 --> 00:37:29.360
And also in this annotation we see
an interest in teaching the student

00:37:29.360 --> 00:37:31.170
about ethnography,
teaching the student

00:37:31.170 --> 00:37:34.370
about the customs of
different peoples.

00:37:34.370 --> 00:37:42.390 position:56%
The Ptolemaic map of Greece, the
lower left, this I willingly written

00:37:42.390 --> 00:37:45.990
so that you will know that these
provinces have many products suited

00:37:45.990 --> 00:37:47.440
to the study of the inhabitants,

00:37:47.440 --> 00:37:49.540
that is that are revealing
about the inhabitants.

00:37:49.540 --> 00:37:52.090
So again, an interest
in ethnography,

00:37:52.090 --> 00:37:55.160
an interest in the customs
of different peoples.

00:37:56.910 --> 00:37:59.600
The eighth map of Europe.

00:37:59.600 --> 00:38:02.350
About which also see
Book 1 of our Strabo,

00:38:02.350 --> 00:38:06.320 position:56%
to whom you should have recourse for
such things, rather than to others.

00:38:06.320 --> 00:38:09.420
So he's giving the student advice
about which classical authors

00:38:09.420 --> 00:38:12.030
to consult on which subjects.

00:38:13.870 --> 00:38:16.840
Ptolemaic map of Asia Minor.

00:38:16.840 --> 00:38:20.250
I've explained these things from
Alexander the Great here so that

00:38:20.250 --> 00:38:22.830
by using them, you can
understand what Pliny says

00:38:22.830 --> 00:38:26.120
in Book 5, chapter 29.

00:38:26.120 --> 00:38:31.770
So he's expecting his student to
be very engaged with this material,

00:38:31.770 --> 00:38:37.050
to be comparing information from
one source with that from another.

00:38:38.170 --> 00:38:39.590
Ptolemaic map of Italy.

00:38:39.590 --> 00:38:47.490
Of all the Alpine peoples, are
listed here by Pliny, but you,

00:38:47.490 --> 00:38:50.650
speaking to the student, list
them with their modern names.

00:38:50.650 --> 00:38:54.120
Write the modern names beside
the ancient ones, by conjecture.

00:38:54.120 --> 00:38:56.040
So he's giving the
student an exercise.

00:38:56.040 --> 00:38:58.190
Write out ancient names
from Ptolemy,

00:38:58.190 --> 00:39:02.970
place beside them your best guesses
as to their modern equivalents.

00:39:07.040 --> 00:39:12.030
Some material on the back of the
modern map of the British Isles.

00:39:12.030 --> 00:39:14.530
For since I once crossed over
to Britain in order to get

00:39:14.530 --> 00:39:17.850
to know the English customs and
pursuits, it would be unworthy,

00:39:17.850 --> 00:39:19.210
if I did not add something

00:39:19.210 --> 00:39:22.870
to this map regarding the
hospitality of that people.

00:39:22.870 --> 00:39:27.370
So first of all, this indicates
some of the annotator's travels.

00:39:27.370 --> 00:39:29.810
It also, again, reflects
the annotator's interest

00:39:29.810 --> 00:39:34.500
in the customs of different people.

00:39:34.500 --> 00:39:36.170
So how does this work?

00:39:36.170 --> 00:39:39.620
How does the educational program
in this work compare with that

00:39:39.620 --> 00:39:45.060
in other 16th century
texts that were aimed

00:39:45.060 --> 00:39:48.350 position:56%
at imparting geographical education?

00:39:48.350 --> 00:39:52.130
Well, it turns out to be much more
sophisticated and thus was designed

00:39:52.130 --> 00:39:54.300
for a much more advanced student.

00:39:54.300 --> 00:39:59.040
So here's Peter Apian's
Cosmographicus liber of 1524.

00:39:59.040 --> 00:40:02.350
There's a one-page description
of Africa in this work.

00:40:02.350 --> 00:40:06.560
The annotator could easily write
one page about a river in Asia.

00:40:06.560 --> 00:40:11.990
So he's offering a student a
much higher level of detail.

00:40:11.990 --> 00:40:15.730 position:56%
There's a long list of place names
with their latitudes and longitudes.

00:40:15.730 --> 00:40:18.170
So this is exactly the sort
of mathematical geography

00:40:18.170 --> 00:40:20.910
that one would get
from Ptolemy himself.

00:40:20.910 --> 00:40:27.660
So the book is not adding
much for the student.

00:40:27.660 --> 00:40:30.100
Johannes Honter's Rudimento
cosmographica.

00:40:30.100 --> 00:40:37.020 position:56%
One of the sentences is a list of
the most important cities of Poland.

00:40:37.020 --> 00:40:39.510
Well, that's wonderful
but it's not much detail.

00:40:39.510 --> 00:40:42.720
It's not any analysis.

00:40:42.720 --> 00:40:46.380
So, again, I mean, and what Ptolemy
was basically offering was a list

00:40:46.380 --> 00:40:48.370
of the places in Poland.

00:40:48.370 --> 00:40:52.820
Here we have a list of
classical place names

00:40:52.820 --> 00:40:55.580
with their modern equivalent,
that is a commonality

00:40:55.580 --> 00:41:00.820
between contemporary graphical
text and the annotations.

00:41:00.820 --> 00:41:04.520
So what can we conclude
about the annotator?

00:41:04.520 --> 00:41:05.820
He was Italian.

00:41:05.820 --> 00:41:07.650
He uses mostly Italian sources.

00:41:07.650 --> 00:41:12.070
He occasionally uses an
Italian word in his Latin.

00:41:12.070 --> 00:41:15.170
The banner, as I mentioned before,
across one map of Italy read,

00:41:15.170 --> 00:41:18.490
heroic virtue is inherent
in Italian blood.

00:41:18.490 --> 00:41:20.940
He traveled widely.

00:41:20.940 --> 00:41:25.160
He visited the Hungarian court for
commerce, he mentions at one point.

00:41:25.160 --> 00:41:26.810
He visited Augsburg.

00:41:26.810 --> 00:41:29.300
He traveled to England
and he was familiar

00:41:29.300 --> 00:41:31.930
with English ecclesiastical
writers and seems

00:41:31.930 --> 00:41:34.930
to have visited the
shrine of Thomas Becket.

00:41:34.930 --> 00:41:37.380
It's also possible that
he traveled in Greece.

00:41:37.380 --> 00:41:41.270 position:56%
I'm not entirely certain about that.

00:41:41.270 --> 00:41:45.210
And his overriding interest was
in European classical antiquity.

00:41:45.210 --> 00:41:47.320
The maps of Asia are
lightly annotated.

00:41:47.320 --> 00:41:49.640
The modern maps are
lightly annotated.

00:41:49.640 --> 00:41:51.570
There's no annotation of the map

00:41:51.570 --> 00:41:53.980
of the Holy Land, as
I mentioned before.

00:41:53.980 --> 00:41:58.180
He repeatedly argues against
the great antiquity of Egypt.

00:41:58.180 --> 00:42:03.290
So if Egypt was more ancient than
Greece it would have more prestige,

00:42:03.290 --> 00:42:07.050
so he argues that Egyptian
culture is not that old.

00:42:07.050 --> 00:42:10.180
And he argues that recent
geographical discoveries merely

00:42:10.180 --> 00:42:12.800
repeated the accomplishments
of the ancients.

00:42:12.800 --> 00:42:16.000
So a few conclusions.

00:42:16.000 --> 00:42:18.230
What exactly is this book?

00:42:18.230 --> 00:42:23.000
It was intended for an advance
student of geography, clearly.

00:42:23.000 --> 00:42:26.470
The annotations profess
an interest in ethnography

00:42:26.470 --> 00:42:29.350
and more broadly demonstrate
the great richness

00:42:29.350 --> 00:42:31.310
of classical geography.

00:42:31.310 --> 00:42:33.850
The hiring of a scribe
and careful arrangement

00:42:33.850 --> 00:42:37.260
of the texts indicate a
very expensive production.

00:42:37.260 --> 00:42:40.680
Was this a copy made
for the student?

00:42:40.680 --> 00:42:43.390
So was a scribe hired,
instead of the student

00:42:43.390 --> 00:42:46.790
as he had been instructed writing
these texts in the book himself,

00:42:46.790 --> 00:42:49.320
was a scribe hired
to do that for him?

00:42:49.320 --> 00:42:52.770
Or was this perhaps a fair
copy for the annotator himself?

00:42:52.770 --> 00:42:55.430
I'm not sure.

00:42:55.430 --> 00:42:57.690
Finally, I mentioned before

00:42:57.690 --> 00:43:01.050
that what Princeton had was
only really half the book.

00:43:01.050 --> 00:43:03.840 position:56%
It was the annotated maps without --

00:43:03.840 --> 00:43:06.590
with a text block that
had no annotation.

00:43:06.590 --> 00:43:09.750
And while I was doing this
research I was curious

00:43:09.750 --> 00:43:12.700
about what might have
become of the other half

00:43:12.700 --> 00:43:14.940
of the book, of the annotated text.

00:43:14.940 --> 00:43:16.580
Surely an annotator who was

00:43:16.580 --> 00:43:21.110
so enthusiastic would not have
left the text unannotated.

00:43:21.110 --> 00:43:25.500
It seemed most likely that
the annotated text block

00:43:25.500 --> 00:43:29.820
of the book had been just lost
over time, had been destroyed.

00:43:29.820 --> 00:43:35.870
But through remarkable good
fortunate I managed to discover,

00:43:35.870 --> 00:43:39.740 position:56%
here again is showing the difference
between the two halves of the book,

00:43:39.740 --> 00:43:46.410
I managed to discover the
text block of the 1525 edition

00:43:46.410 --> 00:43:51.760
of Ptolemy's Geography in a private
collection Brussels annotated

00:43:51.760 --> 00:43:54.820
by the same hand.

00:43:54.820 --> 00:44:01.330 position:56%
And the collector who owned the
book has now very generously sold it

00:44:01.330 --> 00:44:04.290
to Princeton and so the two halves

00:44:04.290 --> 00:44:07.050
of this extraordinary book
have now been rejoined

00:44:07.050 --> 00:44:10.150 position:56%
after considerable time spent apart.

