00:56:47.440 --> 00:56:50.550
the Haitian revolution as
the radical instantiation

00:56:50.550 --> 00:56:55.500 position:56%
of enlightenment liberalism in the
Atlantic world, it is not only this.

00:56:55.500 --> 00:56:57.470
So my book considers the aftermath

00:56:57.470 --> 00:57:01.090
of Haiti's radical
anti-colonial gesture within Haiti,

00:57:01.090 --> 00:57:03.110
and specifically the
factional conflicts

00:57:03.110 --> 00:57:05.240
that both shaped the
revolution itself

00:57:05.240 --> 00:57:08.890 position:56%
and conditioned the possible futures
postcolonial independence statehood.

00:57:08.890 --> 00:57:13.430 position:56%
And a brief background here on the
history and the specificity of this,

00:57:13.430 --> 00:57:15.860
because it will be
useful to you, I think.

00:57:15.860 --> 00:57:17.690 position:56%
The newly independent state of Haiti

00:57:17.690 --> 00:57:20.950
in 1804 divided itself
along the same lines

00:57:20.950 --> 00:57:24.430
that had divided it during the
revolutionary period between those

00:57:24.430 --> 00:57:27.940 position:56%
who were liberals, who wished to see
the independent state as a republic,

00:57:27.940 --> 00:57:30.980
and in 1804 they wanted
to proclaim Haiti

00:57:30.980 --> 00:57:34.610
as the last true remaining
place of liberal enlightenment,

00:57:34.610 --> 00:57:37.910
especially after the first
French republic had faltered.

00:57:37.910 --> 00:57:39.210
And then on the other side,

00:57:39.210 --> 00:57:42.990
those who envisioned a
military authoritarian regime.

00:57:42.990 --> 00:57:45.920
These tensions remained
unresolved for the first two years

00:57:45.920 --> 00:57:47.740
of Jean-Jacques Dessalines' rule

00:57:47.740 --> 00:57:51.200
over independent Haiti
from 1804 to 1806.

00:57:51.200 --> 00:57:52.500
And it's important to note here

00:57:52.500 --> 00:57:56.160
that this state never bore
the name of a republic.

00:57:56.160 --> 00:57:58.870
It was a military state
and then an empire.

00:57:58.870 --> 00:58:01.940
And it was Dessalines'
decision to proclaim an empire,

00:58:01.940 --> 00:58:04.860
orchestrated in secret
by his advisors,

00:58:04.860 --> 00:58:07.430
the backers of this
military authoritarian state,

00:58:07.430 --> 00:58:09.670
that more or less sealed his fate.

00:58:09.670 --> 00:58:11.880
The republican faction
staged an uprising

00:58:11.880 --> 00:58:15.800
and assassinated Dessalines
in October 1806.

00:58:15.800 --> 00:58:18.850
So the republican faction
felled the empire,

00:58:18.850 --> 00:58:21.350
but they were unable
to unite the nation.

00:58:21.350 --> 00:58:24.190
Instead, Dessalines'
assassination marked the start

00:58:24.190 --> 00:58:27.680
of an official civil war between
north and south, between monarchy

00:58:27.680 --> 00:58:30.740
and republic, that
lasted until 1820.

00:58:30.740 --> 00:58:34.320 position:56%
And what's so fascinating about this
period to me, and what is so useful

00:58:34.320 --> 00:58:37.710
for understanding the rest of
Haitian history in my mind,

00:58:37.710 --> 00:58:40.420
is that we see two
drastically different versions

00:58:40.420 --> 00:58:44.840
of postcolonial Haitian statehood
play out, vying for hegemony.

00:58:44.840 --> 00:58:46.140
These are possible futures

00:58:46.140 --> 00:58:50.200
of what an abolitionist black
state could or should be.

00:58:50.200 --> 00:58:52.530
And one of the most
salient differences

00:58:52.530 --> 00:58:56.320
between the two sides is
the way that each state used

00:58:56.320 --> 00:58:59.470
and defined the notion
of, liberty, liberty

00:58:59.470 --> 00:59:02.400
or freedom depending on
how you translate it.

00:59:02.400 --> 00:59:05.150
And if we take as given that
both regimes, both the monarchy

00:59:05.150 --> 00:59:09.230
and the republic, agreed that
liberty did mean abolition

00:59:09.230 --> 00:59:12.280
and freedom from chattel
slavery, it is also true

00:59:12.280 --> 00:59:15.370
that they fundamentally disagreed
on its meaning with regard

00:59:15.370 --> 00:59:19.250
to enlightenment principles and
questions of individual rights.

00:59:19.250 --> 00:59:22.940
So did liberty mean
independence from colonial rule

00:59:22.940 --> 00:59:25.110
or did it mean freedom
from arbitrary government

00:59:25.110 --> 00:59:27.280
and the guaranty of
individual rights?

00:59:27.280 --> 00:59:29.500
And this differed in each state.

00:59:29.500 --> 00:59:32.930
In the north, Christophe,
Henri Christophe, the king,

00:59:32.930 --> 00:59:36.450
saw liberty primarily as
independence from colonial rule

00:59:36.450 --> 00:59:39.350
and not as a guarantee
of individual rights.

00:59:39.350 --> 00:59:42.380
Indeed, the two for him
were mutually exclusive.

00:59:42.380 --> 00:59:47.360
His military state turned
monarchy placed individual,

00:59:47.360 --> 00:59:51.060
or rather anti-colonial
independence, above all else.

00:59:51.060 --> 00:59:54.730 position:56%
That meant that individual liberties
and rights had to be sacrificed

00:59:54.730 --> 00:59:57.240
for this greater good
of sovereign statehood.

00:59:57.240 --> 00:59:59.930 position:56%
Conversely, Alexandre Pation's state

00:59:59.930 --> 01:00:03.300 position:56%
in the south finally founded the
republican government that partisans

01:00:03.300 --> 01:00:08.150
of enlightenment liberalism had
been envisioning since 1791.

01:00:08.150 --> 01:00:10.230
His regime embraced the
revolutionary language

01:00:10.230 --> 01:00:13.570
of individual rights and radical
democracy, but it is important

01:00:13.570 --> 01:00:18.760
to note often felt short --
fell short of this in practice.

01:00:18.760 --> 01:00:21.470
So I've elaborated on
these foundational tensions

01:00:21.470 --> 01:00:25.070
in early postcolonial Haiti at
length here because I believe them,

01:00:25.070 --> 01:00:26.580
as I said before, to be central

01:00:26.580 --> 01:00:31.170
to understanding the continued
civil war secessionist regimes

01:00:31.170 --> 01:00:33.760
and regional conflicts that
persisted throughout 19th

01:00:33.760 --> 01:00:36.650
and 20th century Haiti, and
even to the present day.

01:00:36.650 --> 01:00:41.910 position:56%
And more important for our purposes
here, they reveal crucial background

01:00:41.910 --> 01:00:45.910
on the battles over national
identity and cultural legitimacy

01:00:45.910 --> 01:00:49.790
that have marked Haitian
writing since independence.

01:00:49.790 --> 01:00:52.770
For -- while I place great
importance on historical

01:00:52.770 --> 01:00:56.200
and political background here in my
work, my book is ultimately still

01:00:56.200 --> 01:00:58.930
about writing and how
we can use writing

01:00:58.930 --> 01:01:01.670
to trace the continued
residences of civil war

01:01:01.670 --> 01:01:05.110
and regional conflict in Haiti.

01:01:05.110 --> 01:01:08.960
Take, for example -- here,
let me check my time.

01:01:08.960 --> 01:01:10.260
Yeah, we're good.

01:01:10.260 --> 01:01:12.750 position:56%
[Speaking foreign language] or paper
war that occurred between the north

01:01:12.750 --> 01:01:16.200
and south during this 1806
to 1820 civil war period.

01:01:16.200 --> 01:01:19.630
The printed matter that came
out of each regime, the monarchy

01:01:19.630 --> 01:01:23.360
and the republic, supported their
oppositional political agendas.

01:01:23.360 --> 01:01:26.110
So in the north we have
pamphlets, newspapers,

01:01:26.110 --> 01:01:28.500
and essays from the
northern monarchy

01:01:28.500 --> 01:01:32.700
that served a primarily
utilitarian purpose in support

01:01:32.700 --> 01:01:35.770
of the regime's militant
anticolonial agenda.

01:01:35.770 --> 01:01:38.840
In the southern republic, on the
other hand, and this is fascinating

01:01:38.840 --> 01:01:43.150
to witness, writing begins to
take on the emergent modern sense

01:01:43.150 --> 01:01:46.570
of literature as [speaking foreign
language], that is literature

01:01:46.570 --> 01:01:52.190
as imaginative, creative works,
of the autonomous liberal mind.

01:01:52.190 --> 01:01:55.280
And so southerners were doing this
in order to position themselves

01:01:55.280 --> 01:01:58.680
against northern writing and
also to position themselves

01:01:58.680 --> 01:02:01.390
within a world republic of letters

01:02:01.390 --> 01:02:04.200
that supported their
liberal enlightenment agenda.

01:02:04.200 --> 01:02:07.010
They actually did this
via the literary magazine,

01:02:07.010 --> 01:02:10.770
which was itself a recent invention
of the republic of letters.

01:02:10.770 --> 01:02:14.100
So these southern writers
were performing the successes

01:02:14.100 --> 01:02:17.710
of the liberal republican model
by heralding literary writing

01:02:17.710 --> 01:02:20.250
as a direct expression
of the liberal mind

01:02:20.250 --> 01:02:24.270
and the creative intellectual
abilities of the individual author.

01:02:24.270 --> 01:02:30.150
So here the book basically reveals
how writing itself became the

01:02:30.150 --> 01:02:31.880
subject -- excuse me?

