the Caribbean is a necessary

01:04:28.840 --> 01:04:30.300
and productive lens for analysis.

01:04:30.300 --> 01:04:34.760
One final note just
on contributions.

01:04:34.760 --> 01:04:38.020
There's some debates in francophone
postcolonial literary studies

01:04:38.020 --> 01:04:41.220
about this idea of what was
literature and the world republic

01:04:41.220 --> 01:04:45.440
of letters because I think it's
really useful to think here

01:04:45.440 --> 01:04:48.730
about what gets obscured
and what gets highlighted.

01:04:48.730 --> 01:04:52.660
I'm joining up with some other
scholars who are working on sort

01:04:52.660 --> 01:04:55.620
of critiques of the field
to reveal how studies

01:04:55.620 --> 01:04:59.090
of Caribbean literature has failed
to consider, or even register,

01:04:59.090 --> 01:05:01.990
marginal, and in this
sense I mean non-hegemonic

01:05:01.990 --> 01:05:06.710 position:56%
or non-cosmopolitan writing
precisely because it does not engage

01:05:06.710 --> 01:05:09.480
with the market forces of
international recognition

01:05:09.480 --> 01:05:10.880
or world literary debates.

01:05:10.880 --> 01:05:13.580
So I'm identifying
a culture of writing

01:05:13.580 --> 01:05:16.570
from beyond the world republic
of letters on the margins

01:05:16.570 --> 01:05:20.510
of this international literary
field of Paris-based consecration.

01:05:20.510 --> 01:05:25.110
And one note on methodology and
sources by way of transitioning

01:05:25.110 --> 01:05:29.480
to my slides, and also to the
content section of this talk,

01:05:29.480 --> 01:05:34.150
to do this book, to focus on
silences, what's written out

01:05:34.150 --> 01:05:37.320
or delegitimized in scripted
representations of Haiti,

01:05:37.320 --> 01:05:40.000
it was absolutely critical
for me to go back

01:05:40.000 --> 01:05:42.260
to primary sources themselves.

01:05:42.260 --> 01:05:46.030
So the histories that were written
in the 1850's and the 1890's,

01:05:46.030 --> 01:05:49.660
newspapers, essays, rather than
relying on secondary readings

01:05:49.660 --> 01:05:53.030
of that original content and
specifically Anglophone readings.

01:05:53.030 --> 01:05:55.560
And this is something that
I know is sort of widespread

01:05:55.560 --> 01:05:59.460
in everyone's field, but the
need for Haitian studies is so,

01:05:59.460 --> 01:06:06.060 position:56%
so strong because there is this sort
of, not a slippage, but a failure,

01:06:06.060 --> 01:06:09.120
I think, to take account of
when there is this tension,

01:06:09.120 --> 01:06:11.090
the civil war tension that
I'm talking about that sort

01:06:11.090 --> 01:06:13.110
of gets reproduced
throughout the 19th century.

01:06:13.110 --> 01:06:15.540
It also involved a lot of reading.

01:06:15.540 --> 01:06:19.710 position:56%
And so, you know, to the extent that
that's possible for a book project,

01:06:19.710 --> 01:06:22.110
and I certainly have learned as
this is my first book, what is

01:06:22.110 --> 01:06:25.230
and is not possible to take
on, but being able to work here

01:06:25.230 --> 01:06:28.120
at the Library of Congress has
been transformative in that way.

01:06:28.120 --> 01:06:31.640
The library holds so many
Haitian sources from the 19th

01:06:31.640 --> 01:06:34.080
and 20th century, the
most important ones

01:06:34.080 --> 01:06:37.310
but also some really interesting,
lesser-known publications

01:06:37.310 --> 01:06:41.250 position:56%
from Haitian scholars produced
locally, many of which exist outside

01:06:41.250 --> 01:06:44.720
of this Port-au-Prince sphere as
well which has been fantastic.

01:06:44.720 --> 01:06:47.780
So in the final minutes that I
have here I want to highlight two

01:06:47.780 --> 01:06:49.620
of the collections
that I've been using

01:06:49.620 --> 01:06:51.550
that are really critical
to my research.

01:06:51.550 --> 01:06:56.070
So the first is a Haitian
social science journal,

01:06:56.070 --> 01:06:57.370
the [speaking foreign language].

01:06:57.370 --> 01:06:58.670
It's a social science journal.

01:06:58.670 --> 01:07:06.510
It's arguably the most important
20th century social science journal

01:07:06.510 --> 01:07:08.920
in Haiti, and it certainly
the most prolific,

01:07:08.920 --> 01:07:11.880
and still in existence
today as well.

01:07:11.880 --> 01:07:15.720
It's a hugely important
repository of scholarly production

01:07:15.720 --> 01:07:18.540
of locally produced
knowledge in Haiti,

01:07:18.540 --> 01:07:21.030
and the library has a
near complete run of it.

01:07:21.030 --> 01:07:23.480
It's one of the only libraries
that does in microfilm

01:07:23.480 --> 01:07:26.310
or on microfilm [inaudible]
and in bound volumes.

01:07:26.310 --> 01:07:28.260
I will not belabor
this point; however,

01:07:28.260 --> 01:07:29.950
because I already gave
a short talk on it

01:07:29.950 --> 01:07:33.930
at the National Digital Initiatives
Collections as Data Conference here

01:07:33.930 --> 01:07:36.880 position:56%
at the library, so you can just
watch it and learn a little bit more

01:07:36.880 --> 01:07:39.400
about this so I can
skip to the other stuff.

01:07:39.400 --> 01:07:42.730 position:56%
We're also doing an exciting digital
humanities project with this here

01:07:42.730 --> 01:07:45.830
at the library, labs.loc.gov.

01:07:45.830 --> 01:07:47.320
So check it out.

01:07:47.320 --> 01:07:50.950
It's on my Twitter but I think it's
the sixth hour and 35 minute mark

01:07:50.950 --> 01:07:54.130
on the YouTube channel for that
conference so check it out.

01:07:54.130 --> 01:07:57.120
Okay, so the second
resource that is --

01:07:57.120 --> 01:08:00.980
that I've been using is this
fascinating manuscript division

01:08:00.980 --> 01:08:04.510
collection called the
Celestine Bencomo Collection.

01:08:04.510 --> 01:08:08.880
The collection holds hundreds of
pieces of archival material related

01:08:08.880 --> 01:08:12.320
to nearly every Haitian head of
state from the 19th and early --

01:08:12.320 --> 01:08:15.040
all of the 19th and then
the early 20th century.

01:08:15.040 --> 01:08:18.600
Just a little bit on this
interesting man, Celestine

01:08:18.600 --> 01:08:23.750
or Celestino Bencomo, served as
the Console of the Republic of Cuba

01:08:23.750 --> 01:08:27.740
in Port-au-Prince on
and off 1909 and 1914.

01:08:27.740 --> 01:08:31.970
And during that time he collected
all sorts of interesting pieces,

01:08:31.970 --> 01:08:35.690
lithographs, painted
portraits, decrees, letters,

01:08:35.690 --> 01:08:39.350
other official documents on
or about Haiti's leaders.

01:08:39.350 --> 01:08:44.500
And he gifted this material to
the U.S. government in 1925,

01:08:44.500 --> 01:08:46.640
at which point the Department
of State transferred it

01:08:46.640 --> 01:08:49.110
over to the Library of Congress.

01:08:49.110 --> 01:08:50.790
And having this fascinating

01:08:50.790 --> 01:08:55.120
and really well-preserved
archival material allowed me

01:08:55.120 --> 01:08:59.250
to do some fun things, some
new analyses on some rare,

01:08:59.250 --> 01:09:01.940
and in some cases, as
far as I know, unique,

01:09:01.940 --> 01:09:03.840
historical documents on Haiti.

01:09:03.840 --> 01:09:06.840
And so specifically here I did a
few other analyses, but this one is

01:09:06.840 --> 01:09:11.280
on the heraldry and coats
of arms of Haitian leaders.

01:09:11.280 --> 01:09:17.560
So what I want to kind of show
is how these coats of arms,

01:09:17.560 --> 01:09:22.310
this heraldic symbolism, reveals
the ruptures and continuities,

01:09:22.310 --> 01:09:25.250
the [inaudible] and
adaptations of symbols of power

01:09:25.250 --> 01:09:27.390
in early postcolonial Haiti.

01:09:27.390 --> 01:09:30.800
And more specifically, I want to
make an argument about the empire

01:09:30.800 --> 01:09:33.460
of Fostou Soluke, you
have his name here,

01:09:33.460 --> 01:09:37.110
who is one of Haiti's least
studied or understood leaders.

01:09:37.110 --> 01:09:41.910
He ruled as an emperor
between 1849 and 1858.

01:09:41.910 --> 01:09:46.080
And there is a black legend that
surrounds the history and legacy

01:09:46.080 --> 01:09:49.230
of his rule that is not too
dissimilar from the memory

01:09:49.230 --> 01:09:51.280
of Napoleon III in France.

01:09:51.280 --> 01:09:54.920
And indeed, the two ruled during
the same period, though it's true

01:09:54.920 --> 01:09:59.040
that Soluke proclaimed his
empire before Louis Napoleon.

01:09:59.040 --> 01:10:02.350
And in this sort of black
legend Soluke is either a symbol

01:10:02.350 --> 01:10:06.530
of violence and cruelty or of
ignorance and pure mimicry.

01:10:06.530 --> 01:10:10.390 position:56%
The truth is, of course, somewhere
in between, or maybe not even there.

01:10:10.390 --> 01:10:14.270
But it's true that Soluke's legacy
and memory is heavily mediated

01:10:14.270 --> 01:10:17.830
by his detractors' depiction of
him, especially because there's

01:10:17.830 --> 01:10:21.530
so little self-representation from
his regime in the way of writing,

01:10:21.530 --> 01:10:26.400
artwork, or propaganda, which is
why this Bencomo Collection has

01:10:26.400 --> 01:10:29.410
so many original documents
is amazing because we're able

01:10:29.410 --> 01:10:33.800
to see some of what the documents
coming from his regime looks

01:10:33.800 --> 01:10:35.430
like and some of the images.

01:10:35.430 --> 01:10:40.130
And just a side note, Soluke is
best known for Solukery [phonetic],

01:10:40.130 --> 01:10:42.880
which were basically French
republican caricatures,

01:10:42.880 --> 01:10:48.300
detractors of Napoleon III's
regime who used the image

01:10:48.300 --> 01:10:52.040
of a black emperor in Haiti
to ridicule the return

01:10:52.040 --> 01:10:54.490
to empire under Louis Napoleon.

01:10:54.490 --> 01:10:57.300
And so what I'm trying to
do with these images is sort

01:10:57.300 --> 01:11:00.500
of understand more about
this particular leader.

01:11:00.500 --> 01:11:02.680
So let's just look
briefly at the images

01:11:02.680 --> 01:11:05.680 position:56%
and I'll do a little comparison just
to show you how I did my reading

01:11:05.680 --> 01:11:07.270 position:56%
and analysis of these coats of arms.

01:11:07.270 --> 01:11:09.400
So here you have -- and
what's really fascinating

01:11:09.400 --> 01:11:12.020 position:56%
with the Bencomo Collection is you
have a bunch of different documents,

01:11:12.020 --> 01:11:14.820
so I was able to look at the
variation of these coats of arms.

01:11:14.820 --> 01:11:18.300
And in fact, you know, for Soluke I
think I found four different ones,

01:11:18.300 --> 01:11:20.330
for Christophe there were six.

01:11:20.330 --> 01:11:23.890
So it's interesting to see that
there were different printers

01:11:23.890 --> 01:11:27.460
and different images, or
not images rather plates

01:11:27.460 --> 01:11:29.160
that they were using for these.

01:11:29.160 --> 01:11:30.690
So let me show you
the first comparison.

01:11:30.690 --> 01:11:36.160
So here we have Napoleon I's coat
of arms, 1805, and Dessalines' coat

01:11:36.160 --> 01:11:37.640
of arms just to show you --

01:11:37.640 --> 01:11:41.750
what I want to show you is how
Soluke builds his out more or less

01:11:41.750 --> 01:11:43.940
from these prior leaders.

01:11:43.940 --> 01:11:46.480
What's fascinating, and
these are not actually

01:11:46.480 --> 01:11:48.710
in the Bencomo Collection,
unfortunately, although there is --

01:11:48.710 --> 01:11:52.080
there are a few documents
from Dessalines, which is --

01:11:52.080 --> 01:11:54.450
which is great, even
from [inaudible].

01:11:54.450 --> 01:11:56.190
But you see here, there's
a really big difference.

01:11:56.190 --> 01:11:59.980
And Dessalines created his
coat of arms after Napoleon I.

01:11:59.980 --> 01:12:01.960
There's a little bit

01:12:01.960 --> 01:12:05.800
of an interesting thing
going on in history here.

01:12:05.800 --> 01:12:11.000 position:56%
They -- it appears that Desslines
backdated all of his decrees and all

01:12:11.000 --> 01:12:15.060
of the official nominations of
him as emperor to make it look

01:12:15.060 --> 01:12:19.180
like he nominated himself, or
was nominated before Napoleon,

01:12:19.180 --> 01:12:24.350
but it's not true, or that's
what it most likely looks like.

01:12:24.350 --> 01:12:27.380
And it's a compelling argument,
I believe that to be the case.

01:12:27.380 --> 01:12:31.090
In any case, so we're going on the
idea that Dessalines created his --

01:12:31.090 --> 01:12:36.590
oh no, Dessalines created his
coat of arms off of Napoleon I.

01:12:36.590 --> 01:12:39.770
But as you see here, there
really isn't that much

01:12:39.770 --> 01:12:41.070
that they're working on, right?

01:12:41.070 --> 01:12:42.370 position:56%
There isn't that much that's shared.

01:12:42.370 --> 01:12:45.230
We have the lions in Dessalines,
you have the [inaudible],

01:12:45.230 --> 01:12:48.000
which is significant in
French revolutionary imagery

01:12:48.000 --> 01:12:51.790
but also the importance of
the rooster in Hispaniola

01:12:51.790 --> 01:12:55.290
and in the specific [inaudible]
case is also interesting.

01:12:55.290 --> 01:12:58.270
So I'll come back so that you can
see some of the other comparisons.

01:12:58.270 --> 01:13:01.150
Then we come to Henri
Christophe's coat of arms,

01:13:01.150 --> 01:13:05.330
which is a significant departure
from Dessalines but brings some

01:13:05.330 --> 01:13:08.190
of the Dessalines image
in and also then starts

01:13:08.190 --> 01:13:12.360
to look a little bit more like a
more typical or characteristic,

01:13:12.360 --> 01:13:18.860
a more real symbol, perhaps closer
to Napoleon or more generally

01:13:18.860 --> 01:13:22.750
to a coat of arms as it would
look in any regime of that sort.

01:13:22.750 --> 01:13:25.330
I'll skip over the details
just for the sake of time,

01:13:25.330 --> 01:13:27.450
but it's interesting to
remark the different ones

01:13:27.450 --> 01:13:29.170
that I was able to find.

01:13:29.170 --> 01:13:31.950
And then here you can
see the comparison now

01:13:31.950 --> 01:13:34.270
to what Soluke came up with.

01:13:34.270 --> 01:13:37.660
And so it's interesting because
Soluke basically, I think,

01:13:37.660 --> 01:13:41.990
reinterprets Napoleon I's coat
of arms through Dessalines

01:13:41.990 --> 01:13:43.710
and Christophe's adaptations.

01:13:43.710 --> 01:13:47.410
So he's creating something
that's wholly derivative

01:13:47.410 --> 01:13:50.300
but entirely new at the same time.

01:13:50.300 --> 01:13:54.180
He maintains the two lions, and
his lions, I think, look much more

01:13:54.180 --> 01:13:56.180
like Christophe's than
like Dessalines,

01:13:56.180 --> 01:13:58.590
but the way that they're
turned also evokes Dessalines,

01:13:58.590 --> 01:14:00.550
which is really interesting.

01:14:00.550 --> 01:14:03.360
He returns the eagle
to the shield instead

01:14:03.360 --> 01:14:06.920
of the [speaking foreign language]
that Dessalines had or the phoenix

01:14:06.920 --> 01:14:09.530
that Christophe had,
the mythic phoenix.

01:14:09.530 --> 01:14:12.640
He also at the liberty tree,
which I think is interesting.

01:14:12.640 --> 01:14:14.980
This is a republican, the Haitian
[speaking foreign language]

01:14:14.980 --> 01:14:19.660
which is a republican symbol
which leads me to believe

01:14:19.660 --> 01:14:25.820
that he's basically amassing
symbols from prior regimes in order

01:14:25.820 --> 01:14:28.880
to create a more capacious
idea of his power

01:14:28.880 --> 01:14:30.940
and of Haitian national identity.

01:14:30.940 --> 01:14:33.120
Interestingly though,
the most radical gesture

01:14:33.120 --> 01:14:36.880
in this is his addition
of the imperial rope,

01:14:36.880 --> 01:14:39.200
which returns us -- oh, I'll skip.

01:14:39.200 --> 01:14:40.500
Yeah, that was Christophe.

01:14:40.500 --> 01:14:41.800
You can see some of
those similarities.

01:14:41.800 --> 01:14:43.100
And then back to Napoleon I.

01:14:43.100 --> 01:14:46.080
I mean, the imperial robe is
an exact replication of --

01:14:46.080 --> 01:14:48.880
I mean, he basically just
puts all of that on top

01:14:48.880 --> 01:14:50.180
of the Dessalinean [phonetic]

01:14:50.180 --> 01:14:52.020
or Christrophean [phonetic]
imagery there.

01:14:52.020 --> 01:14:55.880
And he actually used this imperial
rope in his coronation ceremony.

01:14:55.880 --> 01:14:57.180
We have images of it.

01:14:57.180 --> 01:14:58.480
So they're in the collection.

01:14:58.480 --> 01:15:00.040
So it's interesting.

01:15:00.040 --> 01:15:04.400
He's -- it's a complete copy
of Napoleon I that's sort

01:15:04.400 --> 01:15:06.590
of dressing this interesting
reinterpretation

01:15:06.590 --> 01:15:09.610
of previous symbols
of Haitian power.

01:15:09.610 --> 01:15:12.330
And so I wonder, by
way of concluding this,

01:15:12.330 --> 01:15:15.310
what that might tell
us about Soluke.

01:15:15.310 --> 01:15:18.850
And as I said before, I
think it points to his savvy

01:15:18.850 --> 01:15:22.980
and an understanding of creating
and using symbols to gesture

01:15:22.980 --> 01:15:27.490
to previous Haitian rulers and to
create this larger sort of idea

01:15:27.490 --> 01:15:29.710
of Haitian national identity.

01:15:29.710 --> 01:15:32.550
But the Napoleon focus,
I mean this is what

01:15:32.550 --> 01:15:34.140
so many historians have pointed to,

01:15:34.140 --> 01:15:36.900
it was just pure imitation
of Napoleon.

01:15:36.900 --> 01:15:41.170
I think there's something certainly
a bit more sophisticated going

01:15:41.170 --> 01:15:45.750
on there, not least of all
because in -- on December 20, 1848,

01:15:45.750 --> 01:15:48.830
Louis Napoleon, Napoleon
III, was elected president

01:15:48.830 --> 01:15:50.570
of the second republic in Haiti.

01:15:50.570 --> 01:15:56.290
And so at the very least we have an
awareness of this fact in this sort

01:15:56.290 --> 01:16:00.210
of return to imperial
Napoleonic symbolism

01:16:00.210 --> 01:16:06.630
and this 1849 heraldic
symbolism from Soluke.

01:16:06.630 --> 01:16:09.060
I think, my own interpretation that
I'm still kind of still working

01:16:09.060 --> 01:16:11.950
through right now, is that it's
actually a really great form

01:16:11.950 --> 01:16:16.280
of sophisticated trolling and
that Soluke actually proceeded

01:16:16.280 --> 01:16:17.580
the [inaudible].

01:16:17.580 --> 01:16:21.110
I mean he was sort of wanting
that perhaps even to happen.

01:16:21.110 --> 01:16:22.800
In any case, I think what we see

01:16:22.800 --> 01:16:27.400
from this analysis is a much more
sophisticated and complex portrait

01:16:27.400 --> 01:16:30.110
of a little studied and
even less understood leader,

01:16:30.110 --> 01:16:31.980
which I was able to undertake.

01:16:31.980 --> 01:16:33.320
So I'll leave it there.

